  "sections": {
    "Background": {
      "text": "Constellation of\nelectrolyte abnormalities\nthat occur secondary to overconsumption of electrolyte-poor liquid with little other sources of nutrition (e.g. drinking a lot of beer and not eating much)\nPoor overall electrolyte intake limits formation of normal renal urea gradient-->inability to excrete sufficient free water\nTotal body sodium may be depleted, yet still may have elevated urinary sodium/\nFENa\ndue to dysfunction of water metabolism\nAttention to proper nutrition during acute illness may obviate need for hypertonic saline",
      "subsections": {},
      "tables": [],
      "links": [
        {
          "text": "electrolyte abnormalities",
          "url": "https://wikem.org/wiki/Electrolyte_abnormalities"
        },
        {
          "text": "FENa",
          "url": "https://wikem.org/wiki/FENa"
        }
      ]
    },
    "Clinical_Features": {
      "text": "History of chronic alcohol ingestion (in a hypotonic form like beer)\nProtein malnutrition\nSeizures\nAltered Mental Status\nWeakness",
